// Semantic direction:
// sha256 and sha512 are the standard collision-resistant hash functions for integrity and signatures.
// sha3_256 uses the Keccak sponge construction; it is the NIST alternative to SHA-2.
// blake3 is faster than SHA-2 on modern CPUs and supports keyed hashing and key derivation.
// blake3_key enables keyed hashing as a MAC; blake3_context enables domain separation.
// hmac authenticates a message: it proves the sender holds hmac_key.
// hmac_constant_time compares two HMACs without leaking timing information about the difference.
// hmac_verify uses hmac_constant_time to prevent timing-oracle attacks on authentication.
// hkdf (HMAC-based Key Derivation Function) derives one or more keys from a shared secret.
// hkdf_extract combines the secret and hkdf_salt into a pseudorandom key.
// hkdf_expand produces hkdf_okm (output keying material) of hkdf_len bytes using hkdf_info.
// hkdf_info is a domain-separation string that binds derived keys to their purpose.
// pbkdf2 is a slow KDF for password hashing; pbkdf2_min_iterations is 600,000 for SHA-256.
// argon2id is the recommended password hashing algorithm: memory-hard and side-channel resistant.
// argon2_memory is the kilobytes of RAM required; higher values resist hardware attacks.
// argon2_encoded is the standard PHC string format: $argon2id$v=19$m=...
// argon2_verify decodes argon2_encoded and checks the password in constant time.
// password_needs_rehash detects when stored hashes use outdated parameters and should be upgraded.
// upgrade_hash re-hashes the password on next login when hash_algorithm_version is outdated.
// merkle_tree is a binary hash tree; merkle_root summarizes a set of leaves in one hash.
// merkle_proof is the sibling path needed to verify a leaf is included in merkle_root.
// merkle_verify_proof recomputes the root from the leaf and proof; it matches if the leaf is valid.

// Primitive flow:
// integrity: sha256(data) -> digest; verify: sha256(data) == expected_digest
// authentication: hmac_sha256(key, message) -> tag; verify: hmac_verify(key, message, tag)
// key derivation: hkdf(secret, salt, info, len) -> derived_key
// password storage: argon2id(password, random_salt, memory, iterations, parallelism) -> argon2_encoded
// password check: argon2_verify(argon2_encoded, password) -> bool
//   password_needs_rehash? -> re-hash on next login -> upgrade_hash
// merkle: compute leaf hashes -> build tree -> merkle_root
//   prove inclusion: merkle_proof(leaf_index) -> sibling hashes
//   verify: merkle_verify_proof(leaf, proof, root) -> bool

// This defines cryptographic hashing, HMAC, HKDF key derivation, Argon2id
// password hashing, and Merkle tree inclusion proofs.
